        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2353286" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17152911273234218749">This Catalan narrative was a primary model and inspiration for Cervantes&apos; Don Quixote and for the picaresque novel more broadly. The globe-trotting Tirant engages the high and low of the medieval social world, fights with and negotiates with Muslim rulers, all while trying to get into the pants of a princess with a frank sexuality that may surprise modern readers. This narrative is also of interest in terms of constructions of identity, at the time forged on religious cleavages, brought to a fev</span>
  <span id="freeText17152911273234218749" style="display:none">This Catalan narrative was a primary model and inspiration for Cervantes' Don Quixote and for the picaresque novel more broadly. The globe-trotting Tirant engages the high and low of the medieval social world, fights with and negotiates with Muslim rulers, all while trying to get into the pants of a princess with a frank sexuality that may surprise modern readers. This narrative is also of interest in terms of constructions of identity, at the time forged on religious cleavages, brought to a fever pitch during the crusades. The book is long (600+ pages) and it might not be the best choice for readers unused to medieval narrative. Apparently Martorell died before finishing it and it was completed by someone else. The writing of this later section is more conventional. </span>
  <a data-text-id="17152911273234218749" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


