<div id="review_501962191" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/501962191" />
    <a title="Asa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1904061-asa"><img alt="Asa" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/501962191?book_show_action=true">Jan 10, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Asa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Asa" href="/user/show/1904061-asa">Asa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1904061-asa?shelf=1001-books">1001-books</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer501962191" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13514770143150030882">This book reminded me of when I was young and there was a period when I was very interested in King Arthur and his knights. I read a lot of stories about them, some modern and some old, and in the old stories all the knights were brave and all the ladies were beautiful, there were quests and challenges and everything was over the top. The good guys were very good and honorable, the bad guys were treacherous and repulsive, the challenges were impossible, everyone wore expensive and colorful cloth</span>
  <span id="freeText13514770143150030882" style="display:none">This book reminded me of when I was young and there was a period when I was very interested in King Arthur and his knights. I read a lot of stories about them, some modern and some old, and in the old stories all the knights were brave and all the ladies were beautiful, there were quests and challenges and everything was over the top. The good guys were very good and honorable, the bad guys were treacherous and repulsive, the challenges were impossible, everyone wore expensive and colorful clothes with gold jewelry and rare stones, the castles were magnificent and the hospitality was lavish, with enormous dinners, flowing wine and gifts to everyone. Tirant lo Blanc is like that, but horribly long (400+ chapters, even though some of them are only page long) and without most of the fun parts, the sense of magic and legend that has kept King Arthur alive all this time. Instead it is filled with bloody wars, people talking a lot and declaring to others and themselves how miserable or happy or in love they are, instants of racism and islamophobia (all the heroes are Christians out to convert the heathens and reclaim the Greek Empire and Constantinople from the Turks), and the glorification of chivalry and knighthood and honor, and, in the middle of it all, passive-aggressive whining from the heroes when the noble ladies they were in love with wouldn't sleep with them despite the importance of chastity and virginity for women in those days. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13514770143150030882" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


